  "prompt": "How do you know I'd your pregnant?",
  "response": "Determining if you're pregnant typically involves recognizing certain signs and symptoms, followed by taking a pregnancy test. Here\u2019s a breakdown:\n\n### **Common Early Signs of Pregnancy**\n1. **Missed Period**: This is often the first sign, especially if your cycles are regular.\n2. **Breast Changes**: Tenderness, swelling, or tingling in the breasts.\n3. **Fatigue**: Feeling unusually tired due to hormonal changes.\n4. **Nausea and/or Vomiting**: Often referred to as \"morning sickness,\" though it can happen at any time.\n5. **Frequent Urination**: Due to hormonal changes and increased blood flow to the kidneys.\n6. **Food Aversions or Cravings**: Suddenly disliking or craving certain foods.\n7. **Mood Swings**: Hormonal fluctuations can affect emotions.\n8. **Light Spotting or Cramping**: This can occur during implantation (when the fertilized egg attaches to the uterus).\n\n### **Confirming Pregnancy**\n1. **Home Pregnancy Test**:\n   - This detects the presence of the hormone **hCG** (human chorionic gonadotropin) in your urine.\n   - It\u2019s most accurate when taken after a missed period.\n   - Follow the instructions carefully for reliable results.\n2. **Blood Test**:\n   - Ordered by a healthcare provider, this also detects hCG and can confirm pregnancy earlier than a urine test.\n3. **Ultrasound**:\n   - This is used later to confirm the pregnancy and check for the baby\u2019s development.\n\n### **When to See a Doctor**\n- If you suspect you\u2019re pregnant, especially if you\u2019ve had a positive home test, schedule an appointment with a healthcare provider for confirmation and prenatal care.\n\nIf you\u2019re experiencing symptoms or have concerns, it\u2019s always best to consult a healthcare professional for accurate advice.",
